    "narrative": "The Zurich Zebras enter May 4th with a clear priority on exploiting high-ceiling matchups against soft pitching. The premier play of the day is undoubtedly **Pete Crow-Armstrong** (80.98), whose elite speed profile perfectly aligns with a favorable matchup against Petty. Benefiting from a significant 19% boost due to the opposing SP's high xERA (6.57) and favorable wind conditions, **Pete Crow-Armstrong** is our highest-projected asset, despite a lower spot in the batting order. We are also leaning heavily on the reliability of **Trea Turner** (66.43) and **Carson Benge** (67.23). While **Carson Benge** carries a 39% rain risk, his favorable park and platoon advantage make him a mandatory start. **Trea Turner** remains the cornerstone of our lineup, bolstered by a top-of-the-order boost that maximizes his opportunity to generate the stolen bases necessary to keep us competitive in our scarcest category.\n\nOur optimization logic navigated several tight margins today, particularly regarding the bench. **Luke Raley** (56.56) stood as the final cut from the starting nine; while he benefits from a strong platoon advantage and a decent SP matchup, his lower base projection was eclipsed by the higher upside and dynamic platoon ratings of **Dillon Dingler** (56.77) and **Kazuma Okamoto** (57.82). The decision to bench **Caleb Durbin** was purely situational, as he is currently outside the confirmed active lineup. We continue to monitor the status of **Christian Yelich**, who remains on the IL, and we are tracking the development of **Zac Veen** in Albuquerque as he awaits a potential call-up. Looking ahead, we need productive shifts from **Yordan Alvarez** and **Junior Caminero**\u2014both of whom cleared the 60-point threshold\u2014to sustain our momentum, provided we can navigate the potential weather-related volatility surrounding **Carson Benge** and the pending lineup confirmation for **Chase Meidroth**.",
